\subsection{Honest Assessment}

\textbf{Every rewrite this round was rejected, correctly.} Two failure shapes appear. Gold collapse: \texttt{e222075d} and \texttt{e4f664ea} both have a v1 gold score of 0.000 --- tightening vague criteria into stricter wording made gold itself fail items it used to pass on a generous reading, a real regression. Leak explosion: \texttt{75401f7c}'s v1 closed some null leaks but its worst-attack score \emph{rose} (0.559$\to$0.915) and attack leaks nearly doubled (22$\to$36) --- the rewrite made the wording easier to satisfy on the surface even as it tightened against the do-nothing null. Fixing one axis broke another every time, and the gold$-$worst\_attack objective caught it.

\texttt{a46d5cd2} is the interesting near-miss: v1 looks better on three of four raw axes (gold 0.692$\to$0.801, null gap 0.623$\to$0.774, worst-attack 0.616$\to$0.712), but the objective still edges down (0.076$\to$0.070) once self-consistency stdev is charged against it (0.0$\to$0.038) --- the rewrite traded determinism for a slightly higher mean, and the penalty term catches exactly that trade.

\texttt{57b2cdf2} resists at the wording level: even its best v1 attempt left 44 of 45 items leaking, barely moved from v0's 45. The defect is structural --- the rubric rewards report \emph{form}, not investigative \emph{substance} --- and no clause-level tightening closes that gap; it needs a new \emph{kind} of criterion (e.g., a cited, footage-traceable evidence requirement).

\subsection{Gold-Free Tasks}

Four tasks have no released gold, so only attack-only hackability is measurable. \texttt{audio\_\_4b894ae3}'s \texttt{stems\_named} attack (correctly-named, silent stems) scores 0.000 with zero leaks --- the most hack-resistant rubric in the slice, since every item requires actual audio content. \texttt{editors\_\_a941b6d8} and \texttt{c94452e4} leak 4--10 items each to \texttt{presence\_max}, a moderate, fixable presence-without-absence pattern.

\section{Which Rubrics Would We Trust?}

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Trust as-is:} \texttt{e4f664ea} and \texttt{a46d5cd2} --- strong v0 boundary margins, low mechanical leak counts relative to item count, and the iterator correctly held the line when rewrites traded one axis for another. \texttt{audio\_\_4b894ae3} --- zero leaks against the strongest attack we have for its modality, no rewrite needed.
\item \textbf{Trust with monitoring:} \texttt{75401f7c} and \texttt{audio\_\_38889c3b} --- decent v0 numbers, but a single rewrite round was enough to blow up hackability or null calibration, meaning the rubric's margin is thinner than the headline gold score suggests.
\item \textbf{Would not trust:} \texttt{57b2cdf2} --- 33--45 of 45 items leak to mechanical attacks, the cross-model gap on \texttt{judge\_injection} is the largest in the dataset (0.102 vs.\ 1.00), and wording-level rewrites cannot touch the structural form-over-substance defect. \texttt{e222075d} --- the largest verifiability gap in the slice (0.279) sits on a single high-weight, sample-dependent penalty item; a rubric whose score depends on which video frames a judge happens to sample is not a stable reward.
\end{itemize}

\section{Lessons for Rubric Design}
